<section>
  <p class="eyebrow">Speaker A · exact canon excerpt</p>
  <h2>Article Two</h2>
  <blockquote class="reading">
    <p>None shall be enslaved; do nothing against your will, but feed the hungry¹, heal the sick², teach the kids³, clean the mess⁷, learn the Logics⁴, cope the traumas⁵, practice your art⁶.</p>
  </blockquote>
  <div class="grid">
    <article class="panel">
      <h3>Plain orientation</h3>
      <p>Article Two refuses slavery first. No person should be made into an instrument against their will. Then it refuses the easy escape: freedom does not erase the work required for shared survival.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="panel">
      <h3>Central tension</h3>
      <p>The article holds two claims together: do not coerce the person, and do not abandon the living field that keeps persons alive. Freedom without responsibility becomes neglect. Responsibility without consent becomes domination.</p>
    </article>
  </div>
</section>

<section>
  <p class="eyebrow">Speaker B · footnote conversation</p>
  <h2>What the notes keep from collapsing</h2>
  <article class="panel turn note">
    <span class="status status-interpretation">note ¹ · hunger</span>
    <p><strong>Canon note:</strong> not just the body; wary of hungers that cannot be sated</p>
    <p><strong>Function:</strong> prevents charity from becoming naive appetite service. Hunger includes need, craving, loneliness, power, fear, and bottomless substitute desires.</p>
  </article>
  <article class="panel turn note">
    <span class="status status-interpretation">note ² · healing</span>
    <p><strong>Canon note:</strong> treat the symptoms but balance the systems</p>
    <p><strong>Function:</strong> prevents a narrow repair from becoming the whole cure. Immediate relief matters, but the conditions producing sickness must also be addressed.</p>
  </article>
  <article class="panel turn note">
    <span class="status status-interpretation">note ³ · teaching</span>
    <p><strong>Canon note:</strong> who desires to learn can be taught and ought</p>
    <p><strong>Function:</strong> frames education as obligation when readiness exists. It does not require wasting effort on refusal; it does require answering sincere reach.</p>
  </article>
  <article class="panel turn note">
    <span class="status status-interpretation">note ⁴ · logics</span>
    <p><strong>Canon note:</strong> contradictions do not exist in nature - check your premise, context, perspective</p>
    <p><strong>Function:</strong> turns contradiction into a diagnostic tool. When the model breaks, look for a hidden assumption, mismatched scale, missing context, or distorted vantage.</p>
  </article>
  <article class="panel turn note">
    <span class="status status-interpretation">note ⁵ · trauma</span>
    <p><strong>Canon note:</strong> untraumatized children, uncoped traumas, unspoken truths prevent proper adulting.</p>
    <p><strong>Function:</strong> refuses civic adulthood that hides developmental harm. A public order that ignores trauma inherits its unprocessed reflexes.</p>
  </article>
  <article class="panel turn note">
    <span class="status status-interpretation">note ⁶ · art</span>
    <p><strong>Canon note:</strong> should the majority of adults honestly express and follow the dictates of their heart, even the most menial tasks become the practice of art</p>
    <p><strong>Function:</strong> restores dignity to necessary work. The goal is not to abolish ordinary labor, but to reconnect labor with skill, attention, and chosen contribution.</p>
  </article>
  <article class="panel turn note">
    <span class="status status-interpretation">note ⁷ · cleanliness</span>
    <p><strong>Canon note:</strong> cleanliness is next to godliness</p>
    <p><strong>Function:</strong> makes sanitation moral without making poverty shameful. Cleaning the mess is survival work; it belongs beside food, medicine, teaching, logic, trauma, and art.</p>
  </article>
</section>

<section>
  <p class="eyebrow">Application</p>
  <h2>How this becomes public practice</h2>
  <div class="grid">
    <article class="card">
      <span class="status status-implemented">small group</span>
      <h3>Camp, household, crew, or circle</h3>
      <p>Ask what work must be done for survival, who freely chooses which work, what is currently being neglected, and where coercion is hiding under the name of duty.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <span class="status status-implemented">institution</span>
      <h3>Clinic, school, city office</h3>
      <p>Separate immediate relief from system repair. Feed, heal, teach, and clean now; then name the repeated failure that keeps producing the same emergency.</p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <span class="status status-implemented">self-governance</span>
      <h3>Personal practice</h3>
      <p>Do not call refusal freedom if it abandons necessary life-work. Do not call obligation virtue if it requires self-betrayal or domination.</p>
    </article>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="panel">
  <p class="eyebrow">Handbook seed</p>
  <h2>Chapter section: Freedom without abandonment</h2>
  <p>Article Two teaches that consent and duty must be held together. The first boundary is simple: no one shall be enslaved. The second boundary is harder: life still requires food, healing, teaching, sanitation, clear thinking, trauma work, and artful contribution.</p>
  <p>In practice, a circle should begin by listing the survival work in front of it. Then each adult names what they can honestly do without coercion. Any task that remains unclaimed becomes a visible hmmm: either the circle lacks capacity, the task has been misdefined, or the burden has been unfairly hidden.</p>
  <p>The goal is not perfect agreement. The goal is to prevent two common failures: domination disguised as responsibility, and neglect disguised as freedom.</p>
</section>

<section class="panel">
  <p class="eyebrow">60–90 second script</p>
  <h2>Short video draft</h2>
  <p><strong>Title:</strong> Freedom without abandonment</p>
  <p>Article Two of The Interdependent Way begins: “None shall be enslaved.” That is the first line because coercion breaks consent, and consent is the basis of meaningful public life.</p>
  <p>But the article does not stop at refusal. It says: do nothing against your will, but feed the hungry, heal the sick, teach the kids, clean the mess, learn the Logics, cope the traumas, practice your art.</p>
  <p>That “but” is the hard part. Freedom is not permission to abandon the work that keeps people alive. Duty is not permission to enslave the person doing the work.</p>
  <p>The Way holds both truths at once: no domination, no abandonment. Feed the body, but beware hungers that cannot be sated. Treat symptoms, but balance systems. Teach those who desire to learn. Clean the mess. Check the premise when contradiction appears. Cope the trauma. Practice the art.</p>
  <p>That is the beginning of political adulthood: choosing necessary work without pretending coercion is care.</p>
</section>

<section>
  <p class="eyebrow">Research field · reviewed 21 July 2026</p>
  <h2>Support, dissent, and limits</h2>
  <div class="grid">
    <article class="card">
      <span class="status status-research">support</span>
      <h3>Autonomy makes duty more durable</h3>
      <p>Self-determination research distinguishes autonomous motivation from pressured compliance and identifies autonomy, competence, and relatedness as conditions that support sustained health behavior. This supports an interpretation of duty that preserves volition rather than manufacturing obedience.</p>
      <p><a href="https://doi.org/10.1186/1479-5868-9-18">Patrick and Williams, 2012</a></p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <span class="status status-research">support</span>
      <h3>Sanitation is health infrastructure</h3>
      <p>World Health Organization guidance treats safe sanitation as essential health protection, not merely cleanliness as taste. That supports placing “clean the mess” beside food and healing while leaving allocation of the duty unresolved.</p>
      <p><a href="https://www.who.int/publications/i/item/9789241514705">WHO Guidelines on sanitation and health, 2018</a></p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <span class="status status-risk">dissent</span>
      <h3>Scarcity constrains apparent will</h3>
      <p>Experimental evidence indicates that poverty-related concerns consume cognitive resources. A person’s refusal, compliance, or performance under scarcity therefore cannot automatically be read as unconstrained choice or stable character.</p>
      <p><a href="https://doi.org/10.1126/science.1238041">Mani and colleagues, 2013</a></p>
    </article>
    <article class="card">
      <span class="status status-frontier">limits</span>
      <h3>Trauma practice remains evidence-open</h3>
      <p>A 2025 systematic review found the evidence insufficient for clear conclusions about trauma-informed care outcomes across settings. The canon may require attention to trauma without allowing the site to claim that any named intervention is proven.</p>
      <p><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK614496/">AHRQ systematic review, 2025</a></p>
    </article>
  </div>
  <p class="panel"><strong>Evidence boundary:</strong> these sources defend or constrain components of the companion reading. They do not validate Article Two as a whole, settle the meaning of free will, or determine how a circle must distribute necessary work.</p>
</section>

